WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.790 --> 00:00:04.630
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:22.620 --> 00:00:24.190
&gt;&gt; Mary-Jane Deeb: Good
afternoon everyone.

00:00:24.190 --> 00:00:27.450
And thank you for coming.

00:00:27.450 --> 00:00:32.800
And thank you for being here in the
African Middle East Reading Room

00:00:32.800 --> 00:00:39.580
where we are holding, I believe
it's our 27th Conversations

00:00:39.580 --> 00:00:41.830
with African Poets and Writers.

00:00:41.830 --> 00:00:44.590
I'm Mary-Jane Deeb,
chief of the division.

00:00:44.590 --> 00:00:50.570
And I am going to say a few
words about our division,

00:00:50.570 --> 00:00:56.370
which is responsible for the
connections for 78 countries

00:00:56.370 --> 00:01:02.090
in Africa, central Asia, the
Caucuses, and the Middle East.

00:01:02.090 --> 00:01:11.720 position:56%
We want to invite you to come and
use our collections, read our books,

00:01:11.720 --> 00:01:17.650
and follow us on Facebook,
and read our blogs.

00:01:17.650 --> 00:01:25.350
Because all this is a way of us
sharing with you the treasures

00:01:25.350 --> 00:01:29.760
that we have here at
the Library of Congress

00:01:29.760 --> 00:01:32.730
and in the African
Middle East Division.

00:01:32.730 --> 00:01:35.660 position:56%
The Conversations with African Poets

00:01:35.660 --> 00:01:40.210
and Writers was established
here about five years ago.

00:01:40.210 --> 00:01:45.050
And although it started
with an original event more

00:01:45.050 --> 00:01:51.500
than eight years ago when we
had the great writer, Achebe --

00:01:51.500 --> 00:01:53.690
Chinue Achebe -- who
was here with us.

00:01:53.690 --> 00:01:58.850
We also had Ali Mazrui, who
actually launched the series.

00:01:58.850 --> 00:02:04.720 position:56%
But since then we've had about six
programs a year, three in the spring

00:02:04.720 --> 00:02:08.910
and three in the fall
roughly speaking.

00:02:08.910 --> 00:02:16.130 position:56%
And we've done that with the Poetry
and Literature Center at the Library

00:02:16.130 --> 00:02:20.190
that has been established
for a very long time,

00:02:20.190 --> 00:02:26.780
that holds the poet laureate of the
United States, that brings in poets

00:02:26.780 --> 00:02:31.620 position:56%
and writers from all over the world.

00:02:31.620 --> 00:02:37.480
And the Poetry Center
co-sponsors this program.

00:02:37.480 --> 00:02:41.550
We are also co-sponsoring
this program from the onset

00:02:41.550 --> 00:02:47.940
with the African Society of
the National Summit on Africa,

00:02:47.940 --> 00:02:52.440
which is the largest
educational institution focusing

00:02:52.440 --> 00:02:56.720
on Africa throughout
the United States.

00:02:56.720 --> 00:02:58.430
It's an NGO.

00:02:58.430 --> 00:03:08.000
And today we are going to also
inaugurate formally our partnership

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:12.510
with Howard University and with --

00:03:12.510 --> 00:03:16.250
[ Applause ]

00:03:16.250 --> 00:03:25.680
-- who is so well represented by
Professor Mbye Cham, a writer,

00:03:25.680 --> 00:03:31.260
author, film editor, and a
multifaceted and Renaissance man

00:03:31.260 --> 00:03:39.760
who is also joining us in this
partnership on the collection --

00:03:39.760 --> 00:03:43.580
on our Conversations with
African Poets and Writers.

00:03:43.580 --> 00:03:46.650
And now having said that,
I would like to invite him

00:03:46.650 --> 00:03:49.170
to say a few words
about Howard University

00:03:49.170 --> 00:03:52.660
and about himself and this program.

00:03:52.660 --> 00:03:55.340
Thank you.

00:03:55.340 --> 00:03:56.640
&gt;&gt; Mbye Cham: Thank you, Mary Jane.

00:03:56.640 --> 00:03:58.630
Good afternoon.

00:03:58.630 --> 00:03:59.930
It's a pleasure.

00:03:59.930 --> 00:04:06.060
We are really thrilled and
honored to be officially a partner

00:04:06.060 --> 00:04:10.870
in this very important series here.

00:04:10.870 --> 00:04:18.430
And this partnership really builds
on a history of strong relationship

00:04:18.430 --> 00:04:22.520
between Howard University
the Library of Congress,

00:04:22.520 --> 00:04:27.140
particularly the Middle East
Center and African Division.

00:04:27.140 --> 00:04:35.410
We are very happy at the
Center for African Studies.

00:04:35.410 --> 00:04:39.820
It's a new centrally funded
Title VI national resource center

00:04:39.820 --> 00:04:41.340
for African studies.

00:04:41.340 --> 00:04:48.030
At Howard University
we had a grant in 2014.

00:04:48.030 --> 00:04:54.640
And the center basically functions
as a hub to coordinate all

00:04:54.640 --> 00:04:58.810
of the Africa-related research,
teaching, and creative work going

00:04:58.810 --> 00:05:03.730
on at Howard, which is
practically really every school

00:05:03.730 --> 00:05:07.710
and every college in
Africa there's some kind

00:05:07.710 --> 00:05:13.590
of activity going there
related to Africa.

00:05:13.590 --> 00:05:19.890
And the center also does a
lot of promotion and teaching

00:05:19.890 --> 00:05:25.880
of African languages and promoting
also African area studies courses.

00:05:25.880 --> 00:05:28.210
And one of the important components

00:05:28.210 --> 00:05:33.500
of the center is a very robust
outreach program that we have also

00:05:33.500 --> 00:05:38.290
to K-12, community colleges,
minority-serving institutions,

00:05:38.290 --> 00:05:42.720
HBCU's, and four-year colleges.

00:05:42.720 --> 00:05:48.050
And this is something that
we take very seriously.

00:05:48.050 --> 00:05:51.650
It's another avenue,
outlet for us to partner

00:05:51.650 --> 00:05:54.920
with different institutions,
particularly in the area

00:05:54.920 --> 00:06:01.690
to really promote different
portraits, different images,

00:06:01.690 --> 00:06:06.420
different more enabling kind
of understandings of Africa.

00:06:06.420 --> 00:06:11.390
And we're very happy to be part
of this very important series

00:06:11.390 --> 00:06:17.020
that we think is one that
contributes very much

00:06:17.020 --> 00:06:22.080
to creating these different kinds
of understandings of Africa.

00:06:22.080 --> 00:06:27.060
And we're particularly
happy to welcome our guest,

00:06:27.060 --> 00:06:30.580
who will be introduced shortly.

00:06:30.580 --> 00:06:38.220
But just to say thank you very
much for providing us the honor,

00:06:38.220 --> 00:06:45.440
Mary Jane, Patricia, African
Society, to be partners with you

00:06:45.440 --> 00:06:47.030
in this important series here.

00:06:47.030 --> 00:06:48.830
Thank you very much.

00:06:48.830 --> 00:06:52.990
[ Applause ]

00:06:52.990 --> 00:06:54.460
&gt;&gt; Patricia Baine: Good afternoon.

00:06:54.460 --> 00:06:57.650
Welcome to the Conversations
with African Poets and Writers.

00:06:57.650 --> 00:07:04.730
We are honored this afternoon
to be with Mr. Abubakar Ibrahim,

00:07:04.730 --> 00:07:10.990 position:56%
an accomplished African writer and
author and a fine example of what we

00:07:10.990 --> 00:07:13.830
like to call shattering
stereotypes and perceptions

00:07:13.830 --> 00:07:16.570
about a lack of African literature.

00:07:16.570 --> 00:07:17.950
Africa writes.

00:07:17.950 --> 00:07:20.730 position:56%
And so because we have an expression

00:07:20.730 --> 00:07:24.120
at the Africa Society Africa
matters, and so we encourage you

00:07:24.120 --> 00:07:25.900
to read African literature.

00:07:25.900 --> 00:07:28.210
And this exemplifies
the work that we do.

00:07:28.210 --> 00:07:32.080
We engage and educate
Americans about Africa so as

00:07:32.080 --> 00:07:36.070
to create a better understanding of
the continent's peoples, cultures,

00:07:36.070 --> 00:07:38.600
economies, and accomplishments.

00:07:38.600 --> 00:07:42.970
So let's talk a little
bit about Mr. Ibrahim.

00:07:42.970 --> 00:07:46.910
Abubakar Adam Ibrahim
was born in Jos, Nigeria.

00:07:46.910 --> 00:07:50.610
Growing up he always had an
intrinsic desire to write and,

00:07:50.610 --> 00:07:54.470
encouraged by his brother,
he did just that.

00:07:54.470 --> 00:07:57.960
He has written exceptional
pieces of literature.

00:07:57.960 --> 00:08:02.470
His debut collection of short
stories, <i>The Whispering Trees</i>,

00:08:02.470 --> 00:08:07.280
was listed for the Etisalat
Prize for Literature in 2014

00:08:07.280 --> 00:08:10.130
with a title story
that was short-listed

00:08:10.130 --> 00:08:12.880 position:56%
for Caine Prize for African writing.

00:08:12.880 --> 00:08:18.090
His debut novel, <i>Season of Crimson
Blossom</i>, was published in the UK

00:08:18.090 --> 00:08:23.060
by Cassava Republic Press and
tells the captivating story

00:08:23.060 --> 00:08:27.520 position:56%
of an elicit affair between a devout
55-year-old widow and grandmother

00:08:27.520 --> 00:08:30.460
and a street gang leader.

00:08:30.460 --> 00:08:33.160
It takes place in a
conservative Muslim community

00:08:33.160 --> 00:08:39.230
in northern Nigeria, set against
the backdrop of political unrest.

00:08:39.230 --> 00:08:43.960
But Mr. Ibrahim has been the
recipient and has won many awards

00:08:43.960 --> 00:08:48.160
and accolades, including a BBC
African Prize among other awards,

00:08:48.160 --> 00:08:57.140
and a Gabriel Garcia Marquez fellow
and a -- just a second here --

00:08:57.140 --> 00:08:59.400
Civitella Ranieri fellow.

00:08:59.400 --> 00:09:03.440
He was also named in 2014 at
the Hay Festival Africa 39 list

00:09:03.440 --> 00:09:06.090
of the most promising
writers under the age of 40

00:09:06.090 --> 00:09:09.870
who have defined the
future of African writing.

00:09:09.870 --> 00:09:12.420
And I'm sure you will
see that shortly.

00:09:12.420 --> 00:09:15.780
He's also the recipient of
the 2016 Goethe-Institut

00:09:15.780 --> 00:09:19.630
and Sylt Foundation
African Residency Award.

00:09:19.630 --> 00:09:24.650
And I was also able to get
for your own information --

00:09:24.650 --> 00:09:27.870
I asked him to tell me
something that's not

00:09:27.870 --> 00:09:29.560
in here, share with us a hobby.

00:09:29.560 --> 00:09:33.030
And he says to me that he
enjoys watching only Barcelona.

00:09:33.030 --> 00:09:34.560
So.

00:09:34.560 --> 00:09:36.790
[ Laughter ]

00:09:36.790 --> 00:09:40.510 position:56%
So join me in welcoming Mr. Ibrahim.

00:09:40.510 --> 00:09:45.500
[ Applause ]

00:09:51.120 --> 00:09:52.860
&gt;&gt; Abubakar Adam Ibrahim: Hello.

00:09:52.860 --> 00:09:54.480
Good afternoon.

00:09:54.480 --> 00:09:58.800
I'm delighted to be here after
Patricia somehow contrived

00:09:58.800 --> 00:10:02.550
to extract [inaudible] vital
piece of information from me.

00:10:05.140 --> 00:10:07.220
It is a pleasure being here.

00:10:07.220 --> 00:10:11.750
[Inaudible] wonderful people in
the audience to listen to me read.

00:10:11.750 --> 00:10:16.140
I've been told I'm supposed
to read for 15, 20 minutes.

00:10:16.140 --> 00:10:22.680
So I don't have much time,
so I must get onto it.

00:10:22.680 --> 00:10:27.590
So like Patricia said, the book is
principally about the relationship

00:10:27.590 --> 00:10:33.640
between a 55-year-old widow
and a street gang leader

00:10:33.640 --> 00:10:36.330
who is 30 years younger than her.

00:10:36.330 --> 00:10:43.970
And it's set against the backdrop
of [inaudible] in northern Nigeria.

00:10:43.970 --> 00:10:46.010
So the first section
I'm going to read talks

00:10:46.010 --> 00:10:49.070
about a character whose
name is Fa'iza.

00:10:49.070 --> 00:10:53.110 position:56%
She's 15. But she's been
traumatized by some of the tensions,

00:10:53.110 --> 00:10:56.320
but no one really understands
what she's going through.

00:10:56.320 --> 00:10:59.470
But this is what happened to her.

00:11:07.530 --> 00:11:12.140
So that November morning, she knew
she wanted to be by his side --

00:11:12.140 --> 00:11:15.830
by her father's side --
when the news reached them.

00:11:15.830 --> 00:11:18.020
He had returned from the
dawn prayers and was hoping

00:11:18.020 --> 00:11:20.920
to catch the results of the
previous day's elections

00:11:20.920 --> 00:11:22.220
on the BBC Hausa Service.

00:11:22.220 --> 00:11:26.920
He had just turned on
his shortwave radio

00:11:26.920 --> 00:11:30.550
when a neighbor, Umaru
Sanda, barged in.

00:11:30.550 --> 00:11:35.030
"What are you still doing here
when the whole town has gone gaga?"

00:11:35.030 --> 00:11:38.550
But because not even Umaru Sanda's
dimwit wife paid much attention

00:11:38.550 --> 00:11:43.090
to Umaru Sanda, her father
hadn't taken any notice.

00:11:43.090 --> 00:11:44.620
How could there be another riot

00:11:44.620 --> 00:11:48.610
when so many policemen had been
deployed for the elections?

00:11:48.610 --> 00:11:52.060
But the sounds of gunshots drawing
ever closer vindicated Sanda,

00:11:52.060 --> 00:11:56.550
who had since left to
evacuate his family.

00:11:56.550 --> 00:12:01.090
Because they had lived through
riots in 2001, 2002, and 2004,

00:12:01.090 --> 00:12:05.150
they knew their neighborhood
was not safe.

00:12:05.150 --> 00:12:07.470
Their likes were far outnumbered.

00:12:07.470 --> 00:12:10.870
So Mua'zu started packing up
valuables, and Jamilu tried

00:12:10.870 --> 00:12:13.270
to roll the mattress off the bed.

00:12:13.270 --> 00:12:17.580
Amina clung to her mother's
wrapper, both were crying.

00:12:17.580 --> 00:12:20.150
Gunshots thundered close by.

00:12:20.150 --> 00:12:22.960
Then the banshee screams of
Umaru Sanda's wife leapt at them

00:12:22.960 --> 00:12:28.380
from across the fence and
shredded, with decided finality,

00:12:28.380 --> 00:12:34.060
any hope they had of the unfolding
nightmare ending before it

00:12:34.060 --> 00:12:36.040
fully manifested.

00:12:36.040 --> 00:12:37.340
"Where is he?

00:12:37.340 --> 00:12:38.640
Where is he?"

00:12:38.640 --> 00:12:40.930
There was a heavy bang on the door.

00:12:40.930 --> 00:12:43.980
Amidst so much screaming
and so many enraged voices,

00:12:43.980 --> 00:12:46.740
no one could be certain
what was happening.

00:12:46.740 --> 00:12:48.260
Mua'zu snapped out
of his stupor first.

00:12:48.260 --> 00:12:51.890
"The bathroom, quick."

00:12:51.890 --> 00:12:53.370
It was the sound of desperation

00:12:53.370 --> 00:12:57.360
in her father's voice
that struck Fa'iza.

00:12:57.360 --> 00:12:58.960
And when she tried
to look into his eyes

00:12:58.960 --> 00:13:01.370
for some reassurance,
he turned his face away.

00:13:01.370 --> 00:13:07.060
They crammed into the bathroom, all
five of them, and locked the door.

00:13:07.060 --> 00:13:11.570 position:56%
In the small space, they waited,
like the cows Fa'iza had seen packed

00:13:11.570 --> 00:13:14.030
into open trucks at
the Yan Awaki market

00:13:14.030 --> 00:13:16.520
on their way to the slaughterhouse.

00:13:16.520 --> 00:13:19.210
The smell of overnight piss
still waiting to be flushed

00:13:19.210 --> 00:13:22.050
in the toilet bowl swelled.

00:13:22.050 --> 00:13:27.780
But above it the raw stench of
fear made Fa'iza's head turn.

00:13:27.780 --> 00:13:31.300
She wanted to bend down
but bumped into Jamilu.

00:13:31.300 --> 00:13:32.700
"Watch it."

00:13:32.700 --> 00:13:34.270
It was a whisper.

00:13:34.270 --> 00:13:38.370
"Shush." Even in that
whispered word,

00:13:38.370 --> 00:13:41.480
there was anxiety in
her father's voice.

00:13:41.480 --> 00:13:44.330
Amina began whimpering and would
have started wailing but for Asabe,

00:13:44.330 --> 00:13:48.770
who held her tightly, hushing her
and suppressing her own cries.

00:13:48.770 --> 00:13:51.730
"Keep her quiet."

00:13:51.730 --> 00:13:54.140
Now there was anger
in Mua'zu's voice.

00:13:54.140 --> 00:13:57.350
Asabe held the girl and
clasped a hand over her mouth.

00:13:57.350 --> 00:13:58.850 position:56%
Then she herself started whimpering,

00:13:58.850 --> 00:14:02.210
her steady drone filling
the silence.

00:14:02.210 --> 00:14:06.050
Jamilu wriggled his way to the top
of the toilet bowel and squatted,

00:14:06.050 --> 00:14:07.720
resting his weight on his legs.

00:14:07.720 --> 00:14:10.440
Fa'iza heaved and wriggled into
the little space her brother

00:14:10.440 --> 00:14:11.870
had vacated.

00:14:11.870 --> 00:14:15.320 position:56%
When they heard the front door being
bashed in, Asabe's stomach rumbled

00:14:15.320 --> 00:14:18.180
like a disgruntled volcano.

00:14:18.180 --> 00:14:21.090
"I want to use the toilet."

00:14:21.090 --> 00:14:24.200
Jamilu's foot slipped and he
hurtled into his father's back.

00:14:24.200 --> 00:14:26.090
They crashed into the door.

00:14:26.090 --> 00:14:28.010
The commotion outside
blanketed the noise

00:14:28.010 --> 00:14:31.420
and they waited, holding
their breath.

00:14:31.420 --> 00:14:34.340
"Ayatul Qursiy," Mua'zu ordered.

00:14:34.340 --> 00:14:38.240
Fa'iza mechanically started
reciting the verse from memory.

00:14:38.240 --> 00:14:39.580
"In the toilet?"

00:14:39.580 --> 00:14:41.370
Jamilu was incredulous.

00:14:41.370 --> 00:14:43.790
"In your hearts."

00:14:43.790 --> 00:14:46.360
But they froze as they heard
the doors being broken down

00:14:46.360 --> 00:14:49.470
and furniture overturned;
the crash of the TV

00:14:49.470 --> 00:14:51.450
and the splintering of glass.

00:14:51.450 --> 00:14:55.740
Some maniac hacked at the wall with
a machete, the angry sound of metal

00:14:55.740 --> 00:15:00.940
on concrete and his hate-filled
scream jarring Fa'iza's nerves.

00:15:00.940 --> 00:15:03.560
The warm smell of shit
bloated and filled the room.

00:15:03.560 --> 00:15:07.750
Fa'iza turned to her mother and
saw her mouth moving mindlessly,

00:15:07.750 --> 00:15:11.430
her face, in the dim light,
glistening with tears and sweat.

00:15:11.430 --> 00:15:17.140
Fa'iza felt a hand searching for
hers and knew it was her father.

00:15:17.140 --> 00:15:20.260
He squeezed it and quickly let go.

00:15:20.260 --> 00:15:23.540
But she still sensed the trembling.

00:15:23.540 --> 00:15:26.340
When they broke down the bathroom
door, her father went first,

00:15:26.340 --> 00:15:28.670
hands raised above his head.

00:15:28.670 --> 00:15:33.370 position:56%
Fa'iza felt a warm liquid run down
her thighs and pool around her feet.

00:15:33.370 --> 00:15:34.670
"Spare my children, please."

00:15:34.670 --> 00:15:40.330
Mua'zu knelt down before the armed
mob that had invaded the house.

00:15:40.330 --> 00:15:41.630
"Kill him.

00:15:41.630 --> 00:15:45.500 position:56%
Kill him. What are you waiting for?"

00:15:45.500 --> 00:15:46.880
It was a woman.

00:15:46.880 --> 00:15:49.870
Fa'iza knew then that she
would never forget the voice

00:15:49.870 --> 00:15:51.170
of that woman.

00:15:51.170 --> 00:15:53.550
She would never forget
the hate in it.

00:15:53.550 --> 00:15:57.110
She perceived the contagious
nature of hate that makes one want

00:15:57.110 --> 00:15:59.430
to murder people they have
never interacted with.

00:15:59.430 --> 00:16:03.680
Or people with whom they have
eaten from the same bowl,

00:16:03.680 --> 00:16:06.350
mourned alongside and
shared laughter,

00:16:06.350 --> 00:16:10.170
people with whom they have nurtured
the verdant canopy of a friendship

00:16:10.170 --> 00:16:13.760
that was on occasions
closer to kinship.

00:16:13.760 --> 00:16:18.670
But that woman's voice, in
one sweep, ripped that canopy,

00:16:18.670 --> 00:16:20.950
letting the pieces fall heavily,

00:16:20.950 --> 00:16:24.200
like shredded foliage
around their feet.

00:16:24.200 --> 00:16:27.650
Fa'iza stepped forward and
saw the face of Jacob James,

00:16:27.650 --> 00:16:31.620
her math teacher, who
always dressed smartly --

00:16:31.620 --> 00:16:35.820
his shirt ironed and tucked
in with a neatly knotted tie.

00:16:35.820 --> 00:16:38.090
The students made fun
of his sturdy brogues

00:16:38.090 --> 00:16:41.330
because they had never seen
him wear any other shoes.

00:16:41.330 --> 00:16:44.040
He always smiled at their jokes.

00:16:44.040 --> 00:16:46.870
But that morning, he
was not smiling.

00:16:46.870 --> 00:16:51.100
His face, made fierce by war paint,
glistened with sweat and opium

00:16:51.100 --> 00:16:55.540
as he raised his machete
and brought it down.

00:16:55.540 --> 00:17:01.250
Bright, red blood, warm and sticky,
splashed across Fa'iza's face

00:17:01.250 --> 00:17:05.090
and dotted, in a fine spray,
the shell-pink night dress

00:17:05.090 --> 00:17:07.390
that her father had bought her.

00:17:08.940 --> 00:17:12.870
So that was the first
section I'm going to read.

00:17:15.030 --> 00:17:19.740
I have an aversion for
depicting violence in my works,

00:17:19.740 --> 00:17:23.990
but because there's a lot of
violence going on in Nigeria

00:17:23.990 --> 00:17:26.370
as a whole and in the
north especially,

00:17:26.370 --> 00:17:30.660
it kind of forms an important
background to the story.

00:17:30.660 --> 00:17:36.180
So I'm going to read a
different section now.

00:17:36.180 --> 00:17:40.380
Like I said, at the heart of
the story there's this affair

00:17:40.380 --> 00:17:47.080
between a 55-year-old woman who
is a devout Muslim, a mother,

00:17:47.080 --> 00:17:52.180 position:56%
and a grandmother with a gang leader
who is 30 years younger than her.

00:17:52.180 --> 00:17:56.140
So in spite of this violence going
on, people still live or attempt

00:17:56.140 --> 00:17:58.040
to live as normally as they can.

00:17:58.040 --> 00:18:00.350
And it can't stop people
from falling in love,

00:18:00.350 --> 00:18:05.670
from having relationships,
even in refugee camps.

00:18:05.670 --> 00:18:08.870
So this is an encounter between
Binta, who is the main character

00:18:08.870 --> 00:18:14.100
in the novel, and her
lover, Hausa Reza.

00:18:14.100 --> 00:18:19.170
She drifted, almost weightlessly,
in the pungent smell of weed.

00:18:19.170 --> 00:18:22.400
It was only when she opened her
eyes and saw him sitting shirtless

00:18:22.400 --> 00:18:25.460
by the window, puffing
on the joint in his hand,

00:18:25.460 --> 00:18:27.970
that she realized where she was.

00:18:27.970 --> 00:18:30.390
Binta stretched and yawned.

00:18:30.390 --> 00:18:34.110
"Hassan, stop smoking that thing
in here, you could get arrested.

00:18:34.110 --> 00:18:35.860 position:56%
Besides, it's giving me a headache."

00:18:35.860 --> 00:18:39.950
With his back turned to her,
she could not see his face.

00:18:39.950 --> 00:18:43.980
She propped herself up on
her elbow and remembered

00:18:43.980 --> 00:18:46.480
that she was naked under the sheet.

00:18:46.480 --> 00:18:49.390
Her clothes were on the
chair across the room.

00:18:49.390 --> 00:18:51.350
She had taken them off
one after the other

00:18:51.350 --> 00:18:55.780
and folded them carefully
while he had waited on the bed.

00:18:55.780 --> 00:18:57.200
"Just action."

00:18:57.200 --> 00:19:00.940
She smiled at the now familiar
tingling that thawed her incise

00:19:00.940 --> 00:19:02.840
as she did up the hook of her bra.

00:19:02.840 --> 00:19:07.170
"You must have been on something."

00:19:08.280 --> 00:19:13.140
He turned to her and smiled and
she saw how handsome he looked,

00:19:13.140 --> 00:19:16.030
how his glazed eyes
seemed so peaceful and

00:19:16.030 --> 00:19:19.880
yet so far away, how
young he really was.

00:19:19.880 --> 00:19:21.690
"Action zalla."

00:19:21.690 --> 00:19:26.260
He raised a joint at her before
putting it back to his lips.

00:19:26.260 --> 00:19:28.820
He looked at her, then
turned back to the window

00:19:28.820 --> 00:19:32.960
and watched the sprinklers
watering the lawn.

00:19:32.960 --> 00:19:34.260
"God, what am I doing?"

00:19:34.260 --> 00:19:38.620
Her voice was low because
she was addressing herself.

00:19:38.620 --> 00:19:41.590
"What?" "I don't know.

00:19:41.590 --> 00:19:42.890
You are so young, Hassan.

00:19:42.890 --> 00:19:46.190
I don't know if this is right."

00:19:46.190 --> 00:19:48.070
"Why must it be right?"

00:19:48.070 --> 00:19:52.640 position:56%
He spoke with a timber in his voice,
the one she had come to associate

00:19:52.640 --> 00:19:55.240
with what she had called
his inner self:

00:19:55.240 --> 00:20:00.020
The dreamy-eyed philosopher
awakened by ganja fumes.

00:20:00.020 --> 00:20:02.390
"Why must anything
be right or wrong?

00:20:02.390 --> 00:20:06.480
Why can't things be
just the way they are?"

00:20:06.480 --> 00:20:07.780
She sighed.

00:20:07.780 --> 00:20:10.250
"When you smoke this thing, I
don't know what it does to you,

00:20:10.250 --> 00:20:12.670
you just talk rubbish sometimes."

00:20:12.670 --> 00:20:15.990
He smiled and put the
joint to his lips.

00:20:15.990 --> 00:20:18.160
"Maybe you should try it."

00:20:18.160 --> 00:20:19.640
"God forbid.

00:20:19.640 --> 00:20:22.950
I want you to quit,
it's killing you."

00:20:22.950 --> 00:20:24.250
He shrugged.

00:20:24.250 --> 00:20:25.930
"What doesn't?

00:20:25.930 --> 00:20:27.980
I will die when I die.

00:20:27.980 --> 00:20:30.810
We all will, you understand?"

00:20:30.810 --> 00:20:33.130
Binta sighed again.

00:20:33.130 --> 00:20:37.820
"My daughter was saying
something earlier today,

00:20:37.820 --> 00:20:40.480
about some stupid flower that
waits a lifetime to bloom.

00:20:40.480 --> 00:20:41.780
Thirty years, she said.

00:20:41.780 --> 00:20:47.630
And when it, after all those
years, it smells like a corpse."

00:20:47.630 --> 00:20:51.920
"Ha ha. What sort of
flower is that?"

00:20:51.920 --> 00:20:55.340
"I was just thinking how
much like that flower I am.

00:20:55.340 --> 00:21:01.210 position:56%
I have waited my whole life to feel
as I do when I'm with you, you know?

00:21:01.210 --> 00:21:03.450
I shouldn't be telling you
such things, but I just need

00:21:03.450 --> 00:21:06.150
to get it off my chest, you know?

00:21:06.150 --> 00:21:08.970
No one has ever made
me feel this way.

00:21:08.970 --> 00:21:11.310
But like that flower, after
all those years waiting,

00:21:11.310 --> 00:21:15.610 position:56%
when I bloom, it doesn't feel right.

00:21:15.610 --> 00:21:18.700
I don't know if you understand me."

00:21:18.700 --> 00:21:21.910
He continued to puff on the joint,
looking disturbingly peaceful.

00:21:21.910 --> 00:21:25.910
"You mean it stinks."

00:21:25.910 --> 00:21:28.690
She surprised herself
with her laughter.

00:21:28.690 --> 00:21:29.990
It rocked her.

00:21:29.990 --> 00:21:33.330
She laughed for a while,
sniffling as she did.

00:21:33.330 --> 00:21:35.780
When she managed to stop,
she wiped away the tears

00:21:35.780 --> 00:21:37.640
from the corners of her eyes.

00:21:37.640 --> 00:21:41.600
But they wouldn't stop, even
after she no longer felt amused.

00:21:41.600 --> 00:21:43.930
That was how she knew
she was actually crying.

00:21:43.930 --> 00:21:48.520
Save the occasional movements
of his hands to guide the joint

00:21:48.520 --> 00:21:51.210
to his lips, he kept still,

00:21:51.210 --> 00:21:54.270
as if reading the cipher
in the curling fumes.

00:21:54.270 --> 00:21:56.870
It took him a while to speak.

00:21:56.870 --> 00:22:01.140
"You know, when I was a young
boy, there was this Eid day,

00:22:01.140 --> 00:22:05.480
and we were so excited
with our new clothes.

00:22:05.480 --> 00:22:08.170
There was this cheap brocade
our father brought for us,

00:22:08.170 --> 00:22:14.500
it was called Shonekan, it was kind
of in vogue then, you understand."

00:22:14.500 --> 00:22:19.800
She knew it; she had bought it
for her children, too, around '93.

00:22:19.800 --> 00:22:22.220
It had been a fallout from
the political campaigns

00:22:22.220 --> 00:22:24.750
when the borders had been
opened to cheap commodities

00:22:24.750 --> 00:22:28.890
that politicians had
used to entice voters.

00:22:28.890 --> 00:22:32.620
All sorts of things had
come in: Salt, sugar,

00:22:32.620 --> 00:22:35.650
strange soaps with too much
soda that scalded the hands

00:22:35.650 --> 00:22:38.150
and bleached clothes,
cheap shiny fabrics

00:22:38.150 --> 00:22:41.230
that colored the water
they were to be washed in;

00:22:41.230 --> 00:22:45.260
petrol with blue, pink,
and green hues.

00:22:45.260 --> 00:22:47.820
But the elections had been
annulled when the military decided

00:22:47.820 --> 00:22:50.810
against handing over
to the civilians.

00:22:50.810 --> 00:22:54.920
Instead Shonekan was put in
charge until he was upended

00:22:54.920 --> 00:22:58.320
in a palace coup not long after.

00:22:58.320 --> 00:23:02.220
His name was given to all
the strange commodities

00:23:02.220 --> 00:23:04.840
that traders had hoarded
from the political campaigns

00:23:04.840 --> 00:23:10.040
and which flooded the markets as
soon as the politicking was over.

00:23:10.040 --> 00:23:13.720
"Mine was white, sparkling
and starched.

00:23:13.720 --> 00:23:16.230
We had just returned from the Eid
and I was going to take it off

00:23:16.230 --> 00:23:21.710
so I wouldn't stain it while I
ate rice and stew, you understand?

00:23:21.710 --> 00:23:25.820
Then Aminu, my little
brother; my half-brother,

00:23:25.820 --> 00:23:27.450
accidentally spilled ink on it."

00:23:27.450 --> 00:23:33.580
He smoked his joint until she
realized he had finished his story.

00:23:33.580 --> 00:23:35.940
When he turned to her
and saw a perplexed face,

00:23:35.940 --> 00:23:37.240
he smiled with glazed eyes.

00:23:37.240 --> 00:23:39.580
"We are like clothes,
you understand.

00:23:39.580 --> 00:23:44.280
We get rumpled and creased and
torn, sometimes irreparably.

00:23:44.280 --> 00:23:49.170
Some of us are stitched
up, patched up.

00:23:49.170 --> 00:23:51.360
Others are discarded.

00:23:51.360 --> 00:23:52.970
Some clothes are fortunate.

00:23:52.970 --> 00:23:54.700
Others are not.

00:23:54.700 --> 00:23:56.990
They are born into
misfortune and ink spills

00:23:56.990 --> 00:24:00.070
and whatnots, you understand?"

00:24:00.070 --> 00:24:03.890
She rolled her eyes, chasing
the meaning of what he had said.

00:24:03.890 --> 00:24:07.250
"Hassan Reza, you are high."

00:24:07.250 --> 00:24:09.530
He raised the stub in his
hand in acknowledgement

00:24:09.530 --> 00:24:12.490
and took one long last drag.

00:24:12.490 --> 00:24:15.180
"You really need to
give up these things.

00:24:15.180 --> 00:24:17.670
Be a good man, for God's sake."

00:24:17.670 --> 00:24:20.040
"I am what I am."

00:24:20.040 --> 00:24:22.190
He crushed the stub in the
ashtray and turned to her.

00:24:22.190 --> 00:24:28.570
"And what about that issue,
about going back to school?"

00:24:28.570 --> 00:24:31.330
He wagged a finger
in front of his face.

00:24:31.330 --> 00:24:34.540
"No talk, just action,
you understand."

00:24:34.540 --> 00:24:36.160
"Seriously, Hassan."

00:24:36.160 --> 00:24:38.660
"No, not now, please.

00:24:38.660 --> 00:24:41.150
I have an important
assignment from my boss.

00:24:41.150 --> 00:24:42.830
Maybe after that."

00:24:42.830 --> 00:24:44.450
"What assignment?"

00:24:44.450 --> 00:24:46.720
"Very important, you understand.

00:24:46.720 --> 00:24:49.520
Very important."

00:24:49.520 --> 00:24:52.870
So that is the second
section of the reading.

00:24:56.010 --> 00:25:05.610
Lastly, I'll read -- so
the whole of this story,

00:25:05.610 --> 00:25:09.330
this relationship takes place
in a very [inaudible] community.

00:25:09.330 --> 00:25:12.790
It's a very close society
where everyone sort

00:25:12.790 --> 00:25:15.220
of knows what everyone is doing.

00:25:15.220 --> 00:25:19.900
So eventually this affair
between Binta and Reza is exposed.

00:25:19.900 --> 00:25:27.430
And this is what happened when
some women found out about it.

00:25:29.930 --> 00:25:32.180
Following the incident at Laraba's,

00:25:32.180 --> 00:25:34.050
thoughts of entirely
forfeiting her studies

00:25:34.050 --> 00:25:37.420
at the madrasa had
crossed her mind overnight.

00:25:37.420 --> 00:25:40.510
But realizing that her silence
would have encouraged these rumors,

00:25:40.510 --> 00:25:44.490
burying her in shame, Binta
decided to face her accusers and,

00:25:44.490 --> 00:25:47.990
before it grew any worse,
put an end to their malice.

00:25:47.990 --> 00:25:49.630
She was still thinking
of the shari'ah's ruling

00:25:49.630 --> 00:25:52.600
on falsely accusing
decent women of depravity

00:25:52.600 --> 00:25:56.540
when she reached the madrasa
and found two groups of women.

00:25:56.540 --> 00:26:00.370
One was huddled around Mariya while
she tried to interest them in wares

00:26:00.370 --> 00:26:05.750
from the huge bag beneath her desk;
make-up kits, perfumes from Arabia,

00:26:05.750 --> 00:26:10.020
henna from India, bottled
honey and the usual variety

00:26:10.020 --> 00:26:12.480
of sex boosters and creams.

00:26:12.480 --> 00:26:16.150 position:56%
Another group had formed at the
back, clustered around Mallama Umma,

00:26:16.150 --> 00:26:19.790
going over the previous lessons
under the guidance of the matron.

00:26:19.790 --> 00:26:24.600
Ustaz Nura was not in class,
neither was his wife, Murja.

00:26:24.600 --> 00:26:29.040
Binta was enthralled by some
of the wares on Mariya's desk

00:26:29.040 --> 00:26:30.340 position:56%
and reached for a jar of pure honey.

00:26:30.340 --> 00:26:35.050
When she asked if it was definitely
pure, Mariya scowled at her.

00:26:35.050 --> 00:26:39.560
"Well, it isn't adulterated,
if that's what you mean."

00:26:39.560 --> 00:26:41.500
The other women turned to her.

00:26:41.500 --> 00:26:43.860
Binta felt cowed by the attention.

00:26:43.860 --> 00:26:48.220
"Well, you know, sometimes
people do add sugar."

00:26:48.220 --> 00:26:51.120
"Binta, keep [inaudible]
if you are not buying.

00:26:51.120 --> 00:26:53.520
Who are you to come
here with accusations?

00:26:53.520 --> 00:26:58.150
Imagine the hyena calling the
dog a savage," Mariya hissed.

00:26:58.150 --> 00:27:03.600
That wasn't how Binta imagined
the scenario would play out,

00:27:03.600 --> 00:27:05.480
and before she could
marshal her thoughts, Ladidi,

00:27:05.480 --> 00:27:09.510
the skinny woman famed for
her half-dozen divorces

00:27:09.510 --> 00:27:12.380
and her children fathered
by as many men,

00:27:12.380 --> 00:27:16.530
waved her hand before her
nose and cleared her throat.

00:27:16.530 --> 00:27:18.220
"What is that God-awful smell?"

00:27:18.220 --> 00:27:21.990
The women sniffed the air and,

00:27:21.990 --> 00:27:24.420
having failed to perceive
it, they turned to Ladidi.

00:27:24.420 --> 00:27:29.720
After an appropriate interval, in
which Ladidi savored the attention,

00:27:29.720 --> 00:27:36.320
she made a declaration that
stunned the entire class,

00:27:36.320 --> 00:27:38.110
including Mallama Umma's
earnest group devoted

00:27:38.110 --> 00:27:40.980
to the study of hadith at the rear.

00:27:40.980 --> 00:27:44.200
"It's the smell of zina, wallahi.

00:27:44.200 --> 00:27:46.520
I could perceive it from anywhere.

00:27:46.520 --> 00:27:48.060
There is a fornicator
in this class."

00:27:48.060 --> 00:27:53.270
And she spat and turned
her back to the slimy mucus

00:27:53.270 --> 00:27:56.590
that slid sordidly down the wall.

00:27:56.590 --> 00:27:58.920
"Who are you calling
a fornicator, Ladidi?

00:27:58.920 --> 00:28:01.360
Are you making false
accusations against me?

00:28:01.360 --> 00:28:04.420
Can you prove anything?"

00:28:04.420 --> 00:28:05.720
Ladidi chuckled.

00:28:05.720 --> 00:28:08.490
"Who mentioned your name?"

00:28:08.490 --> 00:28:09.900
she hissed.

00:28:09.900 --> 00:28:13.090 position:56%
"But did they not say a guilty
person would sweat even in the rain?

00:28:13.090 --> 00:28:16.160
Aikin banza."

00:28:16.160 --> 00:28:19.030
Binta put down the bottle
of honey on the table and,

00:28:19.030 --> 00:28:20.860
in the heavy silence that followed,

00:28:20.860 --> 00:28:24.020
walked to her seat in
the middle of class.

00:28:24.020 --> 00:28:26.850
She sat down and bowed her head.

00:28:26.850 --> 00:28:31.240
But then Shafa'atu, the young bride
who was stationed just behind her

00:28:31.240 --> 00:28:33.550
and was queasy already with
the burgeoning seed inside her,

00:28:33.550 --> 00:28:38.220
got up abruptly and knocked
over her bag in the process.

00:28:38.220 --> 00:28:40.990
She gathered her books from
the floor and, holding her hand

00:28:40.990 --> 00:28:44.500
over her mouth, hurried
out of the class.

00:28:44.500 --> 00:28:47.200
Ladidi Hassan adjusted her
hijab, spat on the floor,

00:28:47.200 --> 00:28:53.210
cast a sidelong glance at Binta,
whose head was still bowed,

00:28:53.210 --> 00:28:55.750
and walked out of the class.

00:28:55.750 --> 00:28:57.960
Two other women followed her.

00:28:57.960 --> 00:28:59.750
And then Mallama Umma
resumed her tutorials

00:28:59.750 --> 00:29:03.600
with her voice made unnecessarily
loud as to take in the entire class

00:29:03.600 --> 00:29:07.610
and with the fervor that was
driven by restrained furry.

00:29:07.610 --> 00:29:11.070
Binta could hear her, but
she was not listening.

00:29:11.070 --> 00:29:13.370
The words cascaded off her
consciousness and registered only

00:29:13.370 --> 00:29:16.220
in the background of her thoughts.

00:29:16.220 --> 00:29:18.710
Her mind was numbed by the
recollection of the silence

00:29:18.710 --> 00:29:21.360
that had accompanied
her to her seat.

00:29:21.360 --> 00:29:26.250
Her vision was blurred by the film
of tears that lingered in her eyes

00:29:26.250 --> 00:29:29.100
because she would not let
them run down her cheeks.

00:29:29.100 --> 00:29:33.070
She had no idea how long she
sat like that: Head bowed,

00:29:33.070 --> 00:29:37.890
tears imprisoned in her eyes, and
a whistling silence in her mind.

00:29:37.890 --> 00:29:39.580
When she stood up,
she became conscious

00:29:39.580 --> 00:29:42.170
of the abrupt silence around her.

00:29:42.170 --> 00:29:45.430
She picked up her bag and
walked out with as much dignity

00:29:45.430 --> 00:29:48.290
as she could muster,
her pace measured,

00:29:48.290 --> 00:29:52.340
her shoulders held
straight, defiant even.

00:29:52.340 --> 00:29:55.870
But inside, she could feel
the weight of her heart.

00:29:55.870 --> 00:29:59.420
And it felt so much heavier
than she ever remembered.

