00:49:16.270 --> 00:49:19.320
I knew [inaudible]
had written a book.

00:49:19.320 --> 00:49:22.540
And, you know, he's not the
only prominent northerner

00:49:22.540 --> 00:49:23.840
to have written a book.

00:49:23.840 --> 00:49:25.870
Tafawa Balewa, the
first prime minister

00:49:25.870 --> 00:49:28.010
of Nigeria, was an author as well.

00:49:28.010 --> 00:49:31.460
You know? So the tradition
has always been there.

00:49:31.460 --> 00:49:36.750
In terms of book promotion,
I think --

00:49:36.750 --> 00:49:42.410
I don't know, people kind of place
these expectations on authors to --

00:49:42.410 --> 00:49:44.850
and that is because we
don't have the publishing

00:49:44.850 --> 00:49:46.150
structure [inaudible].

00:49:46.150 --> 00:49:51.320
But people have expectations
on writers to be publishers,

00:49:51.320 --> 00:49:53.650
to be book promoters,
to be everything.

00:49:53.650 --> 00:49:55.620
It's simply not possible.

00:49:55.620 --> 00:49:58.830
Some people are good at
writing, that's what they can do.

00:49:58.830 --> 00:50:00.780
Some people are good at
promoting other people's work,

00:50:00.780 --> 00:50:02.160
and that's what they can do.

00:50:02.160 --> 00:50:05.240
So we need the structures, really.

00:50:05.240 --> 00:50:08.580
There are people who are
struggling to be writers,

00:50:08.580 --> 00:50:11.260
who to be honest shouldn't
even bother.

00:50:11.260 --> 00:50:14.500
They should work in
certain [inaudible],

00:50:14.500 --> 00:50:17.750
maybe be editors or something.

00:50:17.750 --> 00:50:20.920
I have people who have written
books and every day they ask me,

00:50:20.920 --> 00:50:22.220
"Where can we find an editor?"

00:50:22.220 --> 00:50:24.320
And you have problems
recommending editors to them

00:50:24.320 --> 00:50:27.000
because there aren't enough
people training themselves

00:50:27.000 --> 00:50:28.300
to become editors.

00:50:28.300 --> 00:50:31.060
You know, everybody wants to
write, everybody wants to publish.

00:50:31.060 --> 00:50:32.360
It's a challenge.

00:50:32.360 --> 00:50:35.740
So there's the need for that
diversification could be there,

00:50:35.740 --> 00:50:37.040
you know?

00:50:37.040 --> 00:50:42.310
So yeah. Religious
freedom and whatnot,

00:50:42.310 --> 00:50:46.550
[inaudible] is a complex case.

00:50:46.550 --> 00:50:49.990
You and I know that, right?

00:50:49.990 --> 00:50:51.950
People use religion.

00:50:51.950 --> 00:50:55.310
And especially the leaders of
that region, they use religion

00:50:55.310 --> 00:51:01.130
as a mechanism to suppress people,
to keep them, you know, subjugated.

00:51:01.130 --> 00:51:03.290
And it is not right,
it is very wrong.

00:51:03.290 --> 00:51:08.310
I remember an instance
where a cousin of mine went

00:51:08.310 --> 00:51:12.530
to serve [inaudible], which
is far up in the north.

00:51:12.530 --> 00:51:16.180 position:56%
And the idea of the youth
services, you know, after graduating

00:51:16.180 --> 00:51:20.540
from university you dedicate
a year to serve your country.

00:51:20.540 --> 00:51:23.540
So you are posted to a different
part from where you come from

00:51:23.540 --> 00:51:26.680
and you cannot participate
in some community services.

00:51:26.680 --> 00:51:30.960
So when he went there, a permanent
citizen of that area said,

00:51:30.960 --> 00:51:35.180
"You know, these are people, the
way you see them, just let them be.

00:51:35.180 --> 00:51:37.580
Don't try to influence them,
don't try to change them.

00:51:37.580 --> 00:51:39.030
They will never change."

00:51:39.030 --> 00:51:41.370
So he couldn't understand.

00:51:41.370 --> 00:51:44.410
So after a few weeks there he
realized what was happening.

00:51:44.410 --> 00:51:47.520
That man, along with a few others,

00:51:47.520 --> 00:51:49.590
[inaudible] people
in that community.

00:51:49.590 --> 00:51:52.460
So there is nothing that a
government would want to do

00:51:52.460 --> 00:51:55.170
to that community that doesn't
have to come through them.

00:51:55.170 --> 00:51:57.690
You know? So they don't want other
people to [inaudible] to come

00:51:57.690 --> 00:52:01.630
and participate in whatever's going
on and sharing ideas and all that.

00:52:01.630 --> 00:52:05.130
So often they get allocations from
governments and they divert them

00:52:05.130 --> 00:52:08.110
to private use and
people don't know.

00:52:08.110 --> 00:52:10.690
Because they are the
ones who are -- you know?

00:52:10.690 --> 00:52:12.060
So we have this issue.

00:52:12.060 --> 00:52:16.220
We have -- I mean, the attacks on
the emir of Kano, for instance,

00:52:16.220 --> 00:52:20.800 position:56%
is he is a religious leader in a
way and he's also a cultural leader,

00:52:20.800 --> 00:52:23.070
but he's speaking the
truths to the north.

00:52:23.070 --> 00:52:25.570
And the north is not
entirely pleased by that

00:52:25.570 --> 00:52:28.590
because they don't expect that
kind of challenge to comes

00:52:28.590 --> 00:52:30.350
from its leaders, you know?

00:52:30.350 --> 00:52:32.500
So we have issues that
we need to deal with.

00:52:32.500 --> 00:52:37.050
And in a way you talk
about religious revivalism,

00:52:37.050 --> 00:52:42.290
which started in the north in the
1970's and continued into the '80s.

00:52:42.290 --> 00:52:44.760
In a way you want to think it's a
good thing, but then you look at it

00:52:44.760 --> 00:52:48.720
and you realize that maybe it's
not such a great thing sometimes.

00:52:48.720 --> 00:52:52.740
Because we have now issues
of fundamentalism going

00:52:52.740 --> 00:52:55.840
on in the north, you have Boko
Haram and all of them sprouted

00:52:55.840 --> 00:52:58.470
from this revivalism and all that.

00:52:58.470 --> 00:53:02.180
So it is also suppressing
conversation.

00:53:02.180 --> 00:53:05.270
And I think that is where I have
a problem with it, you know?

00:53:05.270 --> 00:53:08.630
We need to be more open, we need
to have conversations about things

00:53:08.630 --> 00:53:10.750
in a very civilized context.

00:53:10.750 --> 00:53:13.500
So yeah.

